277
00:13:35,620 --> 00:13:39,529
symmetry. A2B1 is not, there's no particular reason

278
00:13:39,529 --> 00:13:43,439
why A2B1 should be the same as A1B2.

279
00:13:45,160 --> 00:13:48,079
They're two quite different things. But,

280
00:13:48,080 --> 00:13:50,120
if we subtract

281
00:13:50,120 --> 00:13:54,600
ANBM,

282
00:13:54,600 --> 00:13:57,530
in other words, we consider the

283
00:13:57,530 --> 00:14:00,460
tensor made by interchanging A and B.

284
00:14:00,460 --> 00:14:04,460
AM, BN, and ANBM.

285
00:14:04,460 --> 00:14:07,150
If we subtract them, then that

286
00:14:07,150 --> 00:14:09,840
gets rid of all the diagonal elements,

287
00:14:09,840 --> 00:14:13,040
A1B1 minus A1B1,

288
00:14:13,040 --> 00:14:18,060
and it's anti-symmetric because,

289
00:14:18,060 --> 00:14:24,579
it'll contain things like A1B2 minus A2B1.

290
00:14:24,579 --> 00:14:26,069
In the 1, 2 element,

291
00:14:26,069 --> 00:14:27,560
you can see that it's anti-symmetric.

292
00:14:27,560 --> 00:14:29,550
If you interchange N and M,

293
00:14:29,550 --> 00:14:31,540
if you interchange rows and columns,

294
00:14:31,540 --> 00:14:35,500
the two terms will interchange, and so,

295
00:14:35,500 --> 00:14:38,160
what we'll get

296
00:14:38,160 --> 00:14:40,280
is an anti-symmetric tensor.

297
00:14:40,280 --> 00:14:44,719
The anti-symmetric tensor has zeros off the diagonal,

298
00:14:44,719 --> 00:14:46,099
and then,

299
00:14:46,099 --> 00:14:48,020
we'll get,

300
00:14:48,020 --> 00:14:49,020
a 1B2.

301
00:14:49,020 --> 00:14:53,640
It has, for example, in place over here, not A1B2,

302
00:14:53,640 --> 00:14:56,360
but A1B2 minus A2B1.

303
00:14:56,360 --> 00:14:59,360
Let's make it a little bigger.

304
00:14:59,360 --> 00:15:04,900
A1B2 minus A2B1.

