01:28:37,760 --> 01:28:43,760
that we haven't talked about derivatives of fields.

1906
01:28:48,760 --> 01:28:59,760
We've talked about the object dx,

1907
01:28:59,760 --> 01:29:03,760
which might be a little displacement along a world line.

1908
01:29:03,760 --> 01:29:05,760
Now let's come to an entirely,

1909
01:29:05,760 --> 01:29:08,760
what apparently is an entirely different subject,

1910
01:29:08,760 --> 01:29:10,760
a theory of fields.

1911
01:29:10,760 --> 01:29:12,760
Let's forget now particles,

1912
01:29:12,760 --> 01:29:14,760
let's concentrate on fields.

1913
01:29:14,760 --> 01:29:17,760
Fields are things which vary in space-time.

1914
01:29:17,760 --> 01:29:20,260
So they depend in general

1915
01:29:20,260 --> 01:29:22,760
on all four components of position.

1916
01:29:22,760 --> 01:29:23,760
Let's call phi.

1917
01:29:23,760 --> 01:29:24,760
Phi is a field.

1918
01:29:24,760 --> 01:29:26,760
Phi for field.

1919
01:29:26,760 --> 01:29:28,760
It's a scalar field,

1920
01:29:28,760 --> 01:29:31,760
which means it has only one component.

1921
01:29:31,760 --> 01:29:34,760
The simplest possible thing we can make.

1922
01:29:34,760 --> 01:29:37,760
And now we can differentiate it.

1923
01:29:37,760 --> 01:29:39,760
We can differentiate it

1924
01:29:39,760 --> 01:29:42,760
to create d phi

1925
01:29:42,760 --> 01:29:44,760
by dx mu.

1926
01:29:44,760 --> 01:29:46,760
This consists of

1927
01:29:46,760 --> 01:29:48,760
four terms,

1928
01:29:48,760 --> 01:29:50,760
or four components,

1929
01:29:50,760 --> 01:29:52,760
d phi by dx,

1930
01:29:52,760 --> 01:29:54,760
d phi by dy,

1931
01:29:54,760 --> 01:30:00,760
d phi by dz,

1932
01:30:00,760 --> 01:30:06,760
and finally d phi by dt.

1933
01:30:06,760 --> 01:30:08,760
Or d phi by dx1,

1934
01:30:08,760 --> 01:30:09,760
d phi by dx2,

1935
01:30:09,760 --> 01:30:10,760
d phi by dx3,

1936
01:30:10,760 --> 01:30:12,760
and d phi by dx0.

1937
01:30:12,760 --> 01:30:14,760
They form a four vector.

1938
01:30:14,760 --> 01:30:15,760
But,

1939
01:30:15,760 --> 01:30:22,760
they form the covariant components of a four vector.

1940
01:30:22,760 --> 01:30:25,760
They transform slightly differently

1941
01:30:25,760 --> 01:30:28,760
than the components dx mu.

1942
01:30:33,760 --> 01:30:35,760
How do they transform?

1943
01:30:35,760 --> 01:30:38,760
They transform the same way,

1944
01:30:38,760 --> 01:30:40,760
not as dx mu,

1945
01:30:40,760 --> 01:30:43,760
but as dx mu with a lower component.

1946
01:30:43,760 --> 01:30:46,760
Let me remind you what the lower component means.

1947
01:30:46,760 --> 01:30:48,760
The lower component simply means

1948
01:30:48,760 --> 01:30:51,760
you change the sign of the time components.

1949
01:30:51,760 --> 01:30:52,760
No,

1950
01:30:52,760 --> 01:30:54,760
the sign of the space components.

1951
01:30:57,760 --> 01:30:59,760
If d super x mu

1952
01:30:59,760 --> 01:31:00,760
is a set of four numbers

1953
01:31:00,760 --> 01:31:03,760
which form the contravariant components of a vector,

1954
01:31:03,760 --> 01:31:05,760
then this object here

1955
01:31:05,760 --> 01:31:07,760
is just minus

1956
01:31:07,760 --> 01:31:10,760
dx1 dot dot dot dx3,

1957
01:31:10,760 --> 01:31:12,760
minus,

1958
01:31:12,760 --> 01:31:16,760
also dx2,

1959
01:31:16,760 --> 01:31:18,760
and then dx0.

1960
01:31:18,760 --> 01:31:20,760
You change the space components

1961
01:31:20,760 --> 01:31:22,760
and those things define

1962
01:31:22,760 --> 01:31:24,760
the covariant components of a vector.

1963
01:31:24,760 --> 01:31:26,760
It's the same geometric object,

1964
01:31:26,760 --> 01:31:28,760
just being described differently.

1965
01:31:28,760 --> 01:31:31,760
Just being described in a different notation.

1966
01:31:31,760 --> 01:31:33,760
It's useful

1967
01:31:33,760 --> 01:31:35,760
because we can make scalars

1968
01:31:35,760 --> 01:31:40,760
by contracting lower and upper indices.

1969
01:31:40,760 --> 01:31:41,760
Contracting means,

1970
01:31:41,760 --> 01:31:43,760
you take a lower index and an upper index,

1971
01:31:43,760 --> 01:31:45,760
you identify them in sum,

1972
01:31:45,760 --> 01:31:47,760
and that makes

1973
01:31:47,760 --> 01:31:49,760
scalars.

1974
01:31:49,760 --> 01:31:51,760
So it's a useful device.

1975
01:31:51,760 --> 01:31:53,760
It takes into account this extra sign

1976
01:31:53,760 --> 01:31:55,760
in things like

1977
01:31:55,760 --> 01:31:57,260
t squared minus x squared

1978
01:31:57,260 --> 01:31:58,760
minus y squared minus z squared.

1979
01:31:58,760 --> 01:32:00,760
Okay.

1980
01:32:01,760 --> 01:32:03,760
If you were to work out

1981
01:32:05,760 --> 01:32:08,760
the transformation properties of the derivatives,

1982
01:32:08,760 --> 01:32:09,760
now how do you do that?

1983
01:32:09,760 --> 01:32:12,760
You know how the x's themselves transform.

1984
01:32:12,760 --> 01:32:15,760
You know what the coordinate transformations are.

1985
01:32:15,760 --> 01:32:20,760
x1 prime is equal to whatever it is,

1986
01:32:20,760 --> 01:32:22,760
all that Lorentz transformation stuff.

1987
01:32:22,760 --> 01:32:24,760
You know how they transform.

1988
01:32:24,760 --> 01:32:27,760
You know what combinations of the old coordinates,

1989
01:32:27,760 --> 01:32:28,760
the new coordinates are.

1990
01:32:28,760 --> 01:32:30,760
And you can work out,

1991
01:32:30,760 --> 01:32:32,760
you can work out

1992
01:32:32,760 --> 01:32:35,760
the derivatives of the same field phi

1993
01:32:35,760 --> 01:32:38,760
with respect to x prime mu.

1994
01:32:39,760 --> 01:32:41,760
I'm not going to do that on the blackboard,

1995
01:32:41,760 --> 01:32:43,760
it's a little bit tedious.

1996
01:32:43,760 --> 01:32:46,760
We can work it out and see what the connection

1997
01:32:46,760 --> 01:32:50,760
between the derivatives with respect to the prime variables,

1998
01:32:50,760 --> 01:32:52,760
the moving coordinates,

1999
01:32:52,760 --> 01:32:56,760
and the coordinates of the unprimed coordinate frame are.

2000
01:32:56,760 --> 01:33:00,760
And the answer is that they transform the same way,

2001
01:33:00,760 --> 01:33:03,760
not as the dx mu is here,

2002
01:33:03,760 --> 01:33:07,760
but the dx mu is with a lower index.

2003
01:33:09,760 --> 01:33:12,760
That's fairly easy to prove.

2004
01:33:12,760 --> 01:33:15,760
And so this object is a four vector,

2005
01:33:15,760 --> 01:33:21,760
but it forms the covariant components of a four vector.

2006
01:33:21,760 --> 01:33:23,760
These are the four co-

2007
01:33:23,760 --> 01:33:25,760
the, um,

2008
01:33:25,760 --> 01:33:26,760
the co-

2009
01:33:26,760 --> 01:33:29,760
the covariant components of a four vector.

2010
01:33:29,760 --> 01:33:32,760
Is it clear what that means to everybody?

2011
01:33:32,760 --> 01:33:35,760
Just that it transforms in that way.

2012
01:33:35,760 --> 01:33:38,760
It forms a complex of four things.

2013
01:33:39,760 --> 01:33:42,760
Can we make an object with upper components?

2014
01:33:42,760 --> 01:33:45,760
Sure, we can make an object with upper components.

2015
01:33:45,760 --> 01:33:48,760
We just change the sign of the space components

2016
01:33:48,760 --> 01:33:51,760
and leave the sign of the time component alone.

2017
01:33:51,760 --> 01:33:53,760
Alright, so we have two sets of objects.

2018
01:33:53,760 --> 01:33:57,760
We have d phi by dx,

2019
01:33:57,760 --> 01:34:01,760
let's call it one, two, and three,

2020
01:34:01,760 --> 01:34:05,760
together with d phi by dx naught.

2021
01:34:05,760 --> 01:34:08,760
And that's what we call d phi by dx mu.

2022
01:34:09,760 --> 01:34:13,760
Now, we can also consider,

2023
01:34:13,760 --> 01:34:15,760
and this is a definition now,

2024
01:34:21,760 --> 01:34:25,760
d phi by dx with an upper index.

2025
01:34:25,760 --> 01:34:27,260
Instead of the lower index,

2026
01:34:27,260 --> 01:34:28,760
it now has an upper index,

2027
01:34:28,760 --> 01:34:30,760
and that's just the same thing here,

2028
01:34:30,760 --> 01:34:32,760
let's cross this out,

2029
01:34:32,760 --> 01:34:34,760
with a minus sign here.

2030
01:34:34,760 --> 01:34:37,760
In other words,

2031
01:34:37,760 --> 01:34:39,760
the object with the lower index and the upper index

2032
01:34:39,760 --> 01:34:42,760
are related in the same way that all four vectors

2033
01:34:42,760 --> 01:34:47,760
with upper and lower components are related.

2034
01:34:47,760 --> 01:34:50,760
In fact, every time you differentiate an object,

2035
01:34:50,760 --> 01:34:52,760
if you have any tensor,

2036
01:34:52,760 --> 01:34:53,760
or any vector,

2037
01:34:53,760 --> 01:34:55,760
or any scalar,

2038
01:34:55,760 --> 01:35:04,760
and you differentiate it,

2039
01:35:04,760 --> 01:35:07,760
let's suppose you take a vector field.

2040
01:35:07,760 --> 01:35:08,760
Here's some vector field

2041
01:35:08,760 --> 01:35:10,760
that depends on x.

2042
01:35:10,760 --> 01:35:13,760
Let's suppose it has an upper index, for simplicity,

2043
01:35:13,760 --> 01:35:16,760
and you differentiate it

2044
01:35:16,760 --> 01:35:19,760
with respect to x nu.

2045
01:35:19,760 --> 01:35:21,760
That makes a tensor,

2046
01:35:21,760 --> 01:35:24,760
but it makes a tensor with one upper index

2047
01:35:24,760 --> 01:35:27,760
and one lower index.

2048
01:35:27,760 --> 01:35:30,760
Every time the derivative operator acts,

2049
01:35:30,760 --> 01:35:35,760
it simply puts another index on the object.

2050
01:35:35,760 --> 01:35:37,760
So if v is a vector and you differentiate it,

2051
01:35:37,760 --> 01:35:39,760
you get a tensor.

2052
01:35:39,760 --> 01:35:41,760
If v is a tensor and you differentiate it,

2053
01:35:41,760 --> 01:35:43,760
you get an object with yet another index,

2054
01:35:43,760 --> 01:35:44,760
and so forth.

2055
01:35:44,760 --> 01:35:50,760
The differentiation always puts the index downstairs.

2056
01:35:50,760 --> 01:35:53,760
So differentiation is another rule

2057
01:35:53,760 --> 01:35:56,760
that allows you to form vectors.

2058
01:35:56,760 --> 01:36:02,760
Vectors, tensors, and so forth.

2059
01:36:02,760 --> 01:36:04,760
Now what I want to

2060
01:36:04,760 --> 01:36:06,760
discuss for the remaining time today

2061
01:36:06,760 --> 01:36:08,760
is wave equations

2062
01:36:08,760 --> 01:36:11,760
and the invariance of wave equations.

2063
01:36:11,760 --> 01:36:14,760
The invariance of wave equations follows

2064
01:36:14,760 --> 01:36:16,760
if the wave equation has the form

2065
01:36:16,760 --> 01:36:19,760
that some scalar is equal to zero.

2066
01:36:19,760 --> 01:36:24,760
Scalars are the same in every reference frame.

2067
01:36:24,760 --> 01:36:26,260
And so if we can

2068
01:36:26,260 --> 01:36:27,760
write the equation for some wave

2069
01:36:27,760 --> 01:36:31,760
in the form a scalar is equal to zero,

2070
01:36:31,760 --> 01:36:33,260
then we can be sure it's

2071
01:36:33,260 --> 01:36:34,760
the same in every reference frame.

2072
01:36:34,760 --> 01:36:35,760
In other words,

2073
01:36:35,760 --> 01:36:37,760
we can coordinate transform things.

2074
01:36:37,760 --> 01:36:39,760
Let's try to do that.

2075
01:36:39,760 --> 01:36:42,760
Wave equations by their very nature, incidentally,

2076
01:36:42,760 --> 01:36:44,760
always have two derivatives,

2077
01:36:44,760 --> 01:36:45,760
not one derivative.

2078
01:36:45,760 --> 01:36:49,760
They correspond to second derivatives acting on fields.

2079
01:36:49,760 --> 01:36:51,760
Of course, we could imagine

2080
01:36:51,760 --> 01:36:53,760
wave equations with six derivatives,

2081
01:36:53,760 --> 01:36:55,760
but the simplest wave equations, Maxwell's equations,

2082
01:36:55,760 --> 01:36:57,760
other wave equations,

2083
01:36:57,760 --> 01:36:59,760
have second derivatives in them.

2084
01:36:59,760 --> 01:37:02,760
That means that we're going to have a derivative

2085
01:37:02,760 --> 01:37:05,760
and another derivative acting on some field

2086
01:37:05,760 --> 01:37:07,760
that's equal to zero.

2087
01:37:07,760 --> 01:37:09,760
This is a typical example of a wave equation.

2088
01:37:09,760 --> 01:37:11,760
There are other wave equations,

2089
01:37:11,760 --> 01:37:13,760
but let's look for one like that.

2090
01:37:13,760 --> 01:37:15,260
We want it to be

2091
01:37:15,260 --> 01:37:16,760
the same in every reference frame.

2092
01:37:16,760 --> 01:37:18,760
So that means we want it to be

2093
01:37:18,760 --> 01:37:21,760
the left-hand side to be a scalar.

2094
01:37:21,760 --> 01:37:24,760
Left-hand side to be a scalar would be

2095
01:37:24,760 --> 01:37:27,760
one way of going to make a wave equation,

2096
01:37:27,760 --> 01:37:29,760
a single wave equation.

2097
01:37:29,760 --> 01:37:31,760
There's only one way to do it.

2098
01:37:31,760 --> 01:37:33,760
There's really only one way to do it,

2099
01:37:33,760 --> 01:37:34,760
and that's to say,

2100
01:37:34,760 --> 01:37:36,760
we've got to begin by differentiating,

2101
01:37:36,760 --> 01:37:38,760
so let's put mu there.

2102
01:37:38,760 --> 01:37:40,760
The only way to make a scalar out of this

2103
01:37:40,760 --> 01:37:43,760
is to differentiate again

2104
01:37:43,760 --> 01:37:47,760
and to put the index here upstairs.

2105
01:37:47,760 --> 01:37:49,760
What does it mean that the index here is upstairs?

2106
01:37:49,760 --> 01:37:53,760
It means that the space components of the derivative

2107
01:37:53,760 --> 01:37:56,760
are treated with a negative sign.

2108
01:37:56,760 --> 01:37:59,760
This is the simplest wave equation.

2109
01:37:59,760 --> 01:38:02,760
It's invariant because whenever you contract

2110
01:38:02,760 --> 01:38:04,760
a lower index with an upper index,

2111
01:38:04,760 --> 01:38:06,760
it automatically gives you something

2112
01:38:06,760 --> 01:38:10,760
which is invariant under Lorentz transformations.

2113
01:38:10,760 --> 01:38:13,760
So this is the simplest example of a wave equation,

2114
01:38:13,760 --> 01:38:16,760
and let's write out what it actually means.

2115
01:38:16,760 --> 01:38:19,760
Let's write out what it actually means in detail.

2116
01:38:22,760 --> 01:38:25,760
Let's take first the time component.

2117
01:38:25,760 --> 01:38:28,760
The time component is just d0 phi,

2118
01:38:28,760 --> 01:38:32,760
and now the time components don't change sign

2119
01:38:32,760 --> 01:38:34,760
when you raise the index.

2120
01:38:34,760 --> 01:38:38,760
So this is just the second derivative,

2121
01:38:38,760 --> 01:38:42,760
the second derivative with respect to time.

2122
01:38:42,760 --> 01:38:45,760
The first derivatives do change sign

2123
01:38:45,760 --> 01:38:47,760
when you raise an index,

2124
01:38:47,760 --> 01:38:50,760
and so this is minus d second,

2125
01:38:50,760 --> 01:38:56,760
sorry, d second phi by dx squared,

2126
01:38:56,760 --> 01:38:58,760
same thing for y squared,

2127
01:39:01,760 --> 01:39:03,760
same thing for z squared.

2128
01:39:04,760 --> 01:39:10,760
This equation,

2129
01:39:10,760 --> 01:39:18,760
well this is d by dt squared.

2130
01:39:18,760 --> 01:39:21,760
This equation has the virtue

2131
01:39:21,760 --> 01:39:24,760
of being the same in every reference frame.

2132
01:39:24,760 --> 01:39:25,760
How do you check it?

2133
01:39:25,760 --> 01:39:28,260
You write it in a form

2134
01:39:28,260 --> 01:39:30,760
in which it's manifestly just a scalar.

2135
01:39:30,760 --> 01:39:33,760
One index upstairs, one index downstairs.

2136
01:39:33,760 --> 01:39:36,760
That always gives you a scalar.

2137
01:39:36,760 --> 01:39:39,760
That's the simplest wave equation.

2138
01:39:39,760 --> 01:39:41,760
The reason I'm writing it down now

2139
01:39:41,760 --> 01:39:43,760
is because we want to get to Maxwell's equations.

2140
01:39:43,760 --> 01:39:46,760
This is an example of a simple wave equation.

2141
01:39:46,760 --> 01:39:49,760
Maxwell's wave equations are more complicated,

2142
01:39:49,760 --> 01:39:51,760
but we want to get to Maxwell's equations,

2143
01:39:51,760 --> 01:39:53,760
and we want to write them in a form

2144
01:39:53,760 --> 01:39:57,760
which is equally manifestly Lorentz invariant.

2145
01:39:57,760 --> 01:39:58,760
That's our goal.

2146
01:39:58,760 --> 01:39:59,760
We're not going to do that tonight.

2147
01:39:59,760 --> 01:40:00,760
I think we're going to quit now.

2148
01:40:00,760 --> 01:40:02,760
Next time we'll come back and work out Maxwell's equations.

2149
01:40:03,760 --> 01:40:06,760
In a covariant notation,

2150
01:40:06,760 --> 01:40:09,760
they're equations which mix up electric and magnetic fields

2151
01:40:09,760 --> 01:40:12,760
in a somewhat intricate way,

2152
01:40:12,760 --> 01:40:15,760
but they have the virtue of being written,

2153
01:40:15,760 --> 01:40:18,760
or the way we'll write them has

2154
01:40:18,760 --> 01:40:21,760
the virtue of being explicitly Lorentz invariant.

2155
01:40:21,760 --> 01:40:23,760
I'm getting tired, so I think we'll quit.

2156
01:40:23,760 --> 01:40:25,760
Any questions?

2157
01:40:25,760 --> 01:40:28,760
What's that?

2158
01:40:28,760 --> 01:40:31,760
Oh, it could be.

2159
01:40:31,760 --> 01:40:32,760
No, it could be a constant.

2160
01:40:32,760 --> 01:40:35,760
In fact, it could be any number of things.

2161
01:40:35,760 --> 01:40:38,760
It could be any scalar on the right-hand side.

2162
01:40:38,760 --> 01:40:41,760
This is one particular example of a wave equation.

2163
01:40:41,760 --> 01:40:44,260
Another one which is interesting is

2164
01:40:44,260 --> 01:40:46,760
to write a constant here times phi.

2165
01:40:46,760 --> 01:40:48,760
What's on the right-hand side?

2166
01:40:48,760 --> 01:40:50,760
You could have constant times phi squared.

2167
01:40:50,760 --> 01:40:52,760
You could have all kinds of things.

2168
01:40:52,760 --> 01:40:55,760
The simplest equation is just to have zero.

2169
01:40:55,760 --> 01:40:57,760
And we're going to discuss those equations.

2170
01:40:57,760 --> 01:41:00,760
We're going to work them out, study their solutions,

2171
01:41:00,760 --> 01:41:02,760
understand how they behave,

2172
01:41:02,760 --> 01:41:04,260
but this is just the

2173
01:41:04,260 --> 01:41:05,760
simplest example of a wave equation.

2174
